{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0022e394-028f-405b-ae93-a605c0235ef1","content":"In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates one instance **per HTTP request** — each request is a natural scope boundary. In MAUI, there's no equivalent boundary. The app has a single long-lived scope, so `AddScoped` effectively behaves like `AddSingleton`. Your DbContext lives for the entire app session, accumulating tracked entities across navigations.\n\n**Fixes:**\n\n1. **Use `AddTransient`** — new DbContext per injection (simplest).\n2. **Create scopes manually** via `IServiceScopeFactory`:\n   ```csharp\n   using var scope = scopeFactory.CreateScope();\n   var db = scope.ServiceProvider.GetRequiredService<MyDbContext>();\n   ```\n3. **Use DbContext pooling with a factory** (`AddDbContextFactory`) and create/dispose short-lived instances yourself.\n\nOption 3 is generally recommended for MAUI apps since it gives you explicit lifetime control and better performance.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"bebcd5e9-cb29-4623-888f-20a35bf7ff7b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a common pitfall when migrating from ASP.NET Core to .NET MAUI regarding dependency injection scopes and DbContext lifetime management.\n\nIn ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance per HTTP request — each request is a \"scope.\" But in MAUI, there's no concept of an HTTP request. The DI container in MAUI treats `AddScoped` essentially the same as `AddSingleton` because the app has a single long-lived scope (the app's lifetime). There's no automatic scope boundary like an HTTP request.\n\nThis is a well-known gotcha. Let me explain it concisely.","outputTokens":388,"requestId":"981A:7A682:1639BFE:18DDB88:6A0520C0"},"id":"44c6d680-24b6-4770-827f-21747e4e9918","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:09:30.195Z","parentId":"b850b9e8-03b8-4c7f-96fb-e2afd068fa21"}
